    "created_at": "2016-03-15T23:13:12Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-03-15T23:13:12Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Yes, I can see the problem with potentially masking other errors.  That could be mitigated by simply adding the info message without blocking the traceback, so the full original traceback is always visible, only with a catch message:\n\n``` python\ntry:\n  import foo\nexcept ImportError:\n  warn(\"you seem to be missing new dependency foo, see http://url/to/foo to get it\")\n  raise\n```\n\nBut I'm not going to push it :) At least, a little PSA-style announcement on-list when new dependencies arise would be a good idea.  That way, at least the devs who work off master get a heads-up.  In my case, what happened was that I did a git pull but didn't re-run right away, and only noticed the problem on a plane without internet :)  I knew what to do, the git reflog is always my close friend, but a simple heads-up would have saved me a bit of time (esp. later, when I was online and tried to get to the bottom of the problem).\n\nI know the risks of living off master's bleeding edge, but that doesn't mean we can't do a few simple things to soften the edge a little :)\n"
  }
